1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:20,000
I'm Emily Crosby and we're here in the Hattiesburg Public Library with this Glenda Funches on December 2nd, 2015.

3
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:32,000
We're here with the Civil Rights History Project, which is a co-sponsored by the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

4
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:38,000
Also with us is John Bishop and Bill Husschenkar might be joining us later.

5
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:42,000
Thank you Miss Funches for the meal with us.

6
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:48,000
So, thank you. Welcome. Could you tell me when and where you were born?

7
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:59,000
I was born here in Hattiesburg, Mississippi on August 17, 1954, which I always say three months after the decision of Brown versus Blue to Education.

8
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:03,000
How long did it take you to realize that? How long did you get to be?

9
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:11,000
Well, I think I probably realized that after I got in college, there was exactly three months.

10
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:15,000
Can you tell us about your family?

11
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:29,000
Well, I come from a family of 12 children. My mother is originally from Alabama and my father is originally from Jefferson, Davis County, Mississippi, Prentice, Mississippi.

12
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:31,000
What did they do for a living?

13
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:42,000
My mother ended her working career working with the Department of Human Services. She was one of the first homemakers, which was like a social worker aid.

14
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:52,000
And my father, he was a chef at the University of Southern Mississippi. He liked to brag that he worked to about four or five presidents.

15
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:55,000
They gave him a reception when he retired.

16
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:57,000
Really? Yeah.

17
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Was that was your mother doing that work when you were young?

18
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:12,000
Well, basically, she did my nursing sitting with ill people. She would do that.

19
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:15,000
She was ill people, yeah.

20
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:18,000
Where did you fall in the 12 children?

21
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:24,000
I am a little child. There are six under me, so number six.

22
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:28,000
So you must be used to having a lot of people with that on.

23
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:36,000
Actually, my oldest sister had finished high school. By the time I went into first grade, she moved to Cleveland.

24
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:41,000
They called them great migration, she moved up to Cleveland, Ohio.

25
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:44,000
So is she almost like an auntie or something for you?

26
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:48,000
Oh, well, she's like a second mother.

27
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:56,000
So where did you, or what were your community like, how did you broke down now?

28
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Well, it's an opportunity to see a segregated community.

29
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:12,000
And there were black businesses that were thriving. We had cafes, cleaners, nightclubs, and we had hotels.

30
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:22,000
So I got a chance to see the separate society that basically African-American were subjected to in the 50s and 60s.

31
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:26,000
Were you aware of that as a political evidence?

32
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:32,000
Well, I think I became more aware at the freedom summer.

33
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:37,000
Because I was nine, going to summer, freedom summer.

34
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:43,000
And I knew we lived in separate society. We would see whites on the bus.

35
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:50,000
But I think the students with SNCC kind of opened their eyes that we had certain rights.

36
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:53,000
We were not exercising.

37
00:03:53,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Like the public library or the one in public zoo. And those things like that.

38
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:04,000
What did you do for the school?

39
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:12,000
Well, I stored it actually in kindergarten with Miss Maddie Townsend kidding it.

40
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:16,000
And Miss Maddie Townsend was a civil rights activist.

41
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:26,000
Actually, she was one of the first female that there in Lignan who was the circular in the 60s registered to vote.

42
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:35,000
I went to her kindergarten up until the age of six and then I went to Mary Bethel Elementary School,

43
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:44,000
which was my neighborhood. And from there I went to Lily Gurney.

44
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:53,000
That was the year that we started to dismantle the school, dual school system.

45
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:58,000
Had a spot idea of what was called the stair step approach level.

46
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:03,000
And so in 65, 66, they'd be at grade one to four.

47
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:07,000
And then they added four more and 66, 67.

48
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:12,000
And then in 67, 68, the last four grades were added.

49
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:17,000
And that's how 12 grades were desegregated.

50
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:21,000
Was that desegregated with freedom of choice?

51
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:24,000
Freedom of choice. Compliance.

52
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:27,000
Yeah, you know, different, it was separate system.

53
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:31,000
You had to opt out going to the African American school.

54
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:42,000
And I was asked in 1967, 68 to go to Tim's junior high because it was somewhat a distant from the African American community.

55
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:46,000
And they did not have as many blacks at that school.

56
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:52,000
They were about four or five that went that first year and that would have been 66, 67.

57
00:05:52,000 --> 00:06:04,000
So Miss Eurling Bowett who served on the education committee requested from my fingers that we be allowed my sister and I to go to Tim's.

58
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:09,000
Was that the education community with the NAACP?

59
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:11,000
At the NAACP she was.

60
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:13,000
And what did your parents say?

61
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:16,000
Well, they agreed.

62
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:28,000
I think what the NAACP was looking for students who had pretty good grades because they knew going into a hostile education environment that your grades had to be pretty good because you know, it was going to suffer some.

63
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:31,000
So my mother agreed.

64
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:34,000
I'm actually, my mother was working for a family.

65
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:38,000
The guy was paralyzed and she was just nursed.

66
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:41,000
And we went to say school is his son.

67
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:51,000
Now the wife had no problem with it but he, the man who was paralyzed, wanted to know what did the NAACP give her to send her kids to Tim's.

68
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:52,000
Would you know?

69
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:53,000
What did she say?

70
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:55,000
She told her nothing.

71
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:57,000
Nothing.

72
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:04,000
So my sister, Tim's was a junior high and also had an elementary school.

73
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:07,000
So his son was an elementary school.

74
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:11,000
And my sister, two years younger than me, she was an elementary school.

75
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:12,000
And I was in junior high.

76
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:14,000
So did they get an Iraq?

77
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:15,000
I don't think so.

78
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:22,000
No, she was in sixth grade and I think it was maybe about third.

79
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:32,000
So when they asked your parents and your mother agreed, did they talk to you all about whether you wanted to or did they just make the decision for you?

80
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:38,000
Well my next own neighbor, Gwen Bond, she had gone that first year to Hawkins.

81
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:44,000
And every day we would wait for Gwen to get off the bus and brief us on what happened.

82
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:55,000
So we were the opinion that Hawkins was where the poor wife's middle class and we would be going to tell us where the moral floing.

83
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:58,000
From freedom summer, we'd song off.

84
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:02,000
That the poor wife was with embrace integration.

85
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:10,000
So we felt like we might want to have the form the Gwen had, but we found out, hey, then you get reality.

86
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:12,000
Then you get reality.

87
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:16,000
So freedom summer led you to believe that you would have an easier time?

88
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:17,000
With the rich wife.

89
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:21,000
Was that because you associated the volunteers?

90
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:24,000
You know, they were middle class rich.

91
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:25,000
Kids coming south.

92
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:32,000
So you hear about the poor wife's and gravitating to us the clansmen and all that.

93
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:36,000
So we just knew that we were going to have that problem with the rich wife.

94
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:38,000
How did that work out for you?

95
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:40,000
It was a nightmare.

96
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:43,000
I would pitch myself to make sure I wasn't.

97
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:47,000
We were basically, it was a hostile school environment.

98
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:52,000
It went the whole day without anyone talking to us.

99
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:56,000
I think the menace grade of the principal is kind of set to tone.

100
00:08:56,000 --> 00:09:02,000
And I think if he would have instructed the teachers to do these children coming into their environment,

101
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:07,000
make sure you make sure that they feel like they are poor at school.

102
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:11,000
So I was going nine months and no one eating with you.

103
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:14,000
I put my tray down and they would jump up.

104
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:20,000
And quite recently, five years ago, I received a letter from Delaware from a young lady who had gone to town.

105
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:24,000
So, you know, like lady who was a student back then.

106
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:26,000
And she was apologizing to me.

107
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:31,000
She recalled me putting my tray down and she jumping up.

108
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:35,000
My response to her, I sent her letter back accepting her apology.

109
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:39,000
But I don't recall who jumped up because it happened nine months ago.

110
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:43,000
So, you know, you have to know, you don't pay attention to people.

111
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:46,000
You just know you look up through that scenario, put your tray down.

112
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:48,000
Okay, big on-job.

113
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:52,000
But I think the teacher probably could have made it better if she would have came to herself.

114
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:54,000
Thanks for letting me eat with you today.

115
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:57,000
But that didn't happen.

116
00:09:57,000 --> 00:10:00,000
Did the woman who wrote to the apology that she explained?

117
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:02,000
I mean, did she say why she was apologizing?

118
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:07,000
She said she was not a racist, but she was just in hell.

119
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:13,000
She was just not very enough to book the 8-gray system.

120
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:18,000
I mean, you know, I'm sure she would have suffered some type of re-progression if she would have done that.

121
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:21,000
So, she, you know, she tried to frame it.

122
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:25,000
You know, she did it because of her pressure, I guess.

123
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:28,000
Do you know what prompted her at that particular moment?

124
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:30,000
Well, we had done an article.

125
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:32,000
It was on Marlita Keenberg thing.

126
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:36,000
And Marlita Keen had visited my church two weeks before his death.

127
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:40,000
And I had given a civil rights marker in 1999.

128
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:46,000
I think the first one in the state, they had read a big article on that two-page article.

129
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:49,000
And she was home visiting her mother and she saw it.

130
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:55,000
So, she said she looked me up on the internet and sent my address.

131
00:10:55,000 --> 00:10:59,000
The little one to my workplace, not to my home.

132
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:02,000
Her purpose, right?

133
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:06,000
And I invited her next time she come and we get together and maybe we have a lunch.

134
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:07,000
I haven't heard from her.

135
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:11,000
I don't know if she called on my home number or what, but I haven't heard from her.

136
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:16,000
What was it like in the classroom?

137
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:22,000
Well, in the classroom, like I said, from the first day, we were briefed by the principal.

138
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:27,000
We had any problem to report to Mr. Manguno, who was the assistant principal.

139
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:32,000
I was a little late getting into the class so I walked in and took a seat.

140
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:37,000
And immediately the science teacher told me, oh no, we don't let little girls and boys sit together.

141
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:42,000
So she moved me to a table in the front of the classroom on the right-hand side.

142
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:48,000
And there, I sat for the entire school, but I said, you know, it was a table with two chairs.

143
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:50,000
Right, right.

144
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:55,000
And was that true and where it wasn't only girls sitting with girls?

145
00:11:55,000 --> 00:11:56,000
I think so.

146
00:11:56,000 --> 00:11:59,000
Yeah, I probably was.

147
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:01,000
So you sat there by yourself the whole?

148
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:06,000
Yeah, and what did she finally get the nerve asked me, who I did that time?

149
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:11,000
I told her because I had to write.

150
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:16,000
So it's an incident, so I'll do that to semester.

151
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:23,000
I did this paper on Marlotte King because he, I was there when he spoke about the poor people march two weeks before his death.

152
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:27,000
He was here in Hansford on March 19th at Mountainside Church.

153
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:30,000
And so we had to do a history of paper.

154
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:32,000
That's okay, I love history.

155
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:40,000
But all the articles after his death and with the pamphlets that hit, I did it on Marlotte King.

156
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:44,000
So one day the history teacher said, I need to speak to you.

157
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:50,000
And outside of the clients, she said, some of the students got a whole year paper and they cut it up.

158
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:53,000
But you got to eat on it.

159
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:59,000
So it was what incident after another, you know?

160
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:02,000
Did you have much support?

161
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:06,000
Did you talk to other students who were going through different trades or schools?

162
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:09,000
Well, actually we rode a van to school.

163
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:12,000
My next door neighbor had a Volkswagen van.

164
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:18,000
And she picked up about, and asked me how 15, about 15 kids got on it.

165
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:23,000
It's an elementary school aged kids in junior high.

166
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:25,000
And so we were confirmed.

167
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:28,000
I guess she was out of therapists.

168
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:36,000
And really truly, they should have provided some type of counseling because, you know, Mr. Cippy had resisted integration.

169
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:40,000
You know, with the white citizen council and then the sovereign commission.

170
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:48,000
And I think that they dropped the bone in not providing counseling for us.

171
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:53,000
I was in court with a attorney from Hannesburg, up in Jeff Davis County, about two years ago.

172
00:13:53,000 --> 00:14:02,000
And he was telling me about an incident that happened with a young man, an African-American guy, who was there during the time I was there.

173
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:12,000
And someone took their shoes, slapped him in the face with, and the coach said, well, we go to sit here until I find out who did this.

174
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:16,000
So he was interested in knowing where this young man was.

175
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:22,000
And actually we just found out two days ago that he got, he was living in Louisiana.

176
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:25,000
But it was all a type of incident that took place.

177
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:27,000
You know, I love core music.

178
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:29,000
And I took my core music.

179
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:37,000
And for some reason, Mr. Kelly, who was the core music teacher, always selected the third period class to sing.

180
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:44,000
And so we had to sing at the night grade class program.

181
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:46,000
It was like a commencement program for them.

182
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:49,000
And we were practicing on the song.

183
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:58,000
We had to, we had two days to memorize this song, to dream the impossible during.

184
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:02,000
And so I was sitting, this young lady started crying.

185
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:04,000
And everybody was wondering, why was she crying?

186
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:06,000
Here she said, my parents are coming.

187
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:09,000
And they're going to see me standing next to Glenda.

188
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:19,000
And for her, there was, very, she didn't want her parents to see her standing with the second soprano next to her.

189
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:22,000
So she was moved, somebody was moved.

190
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:24,000
We were not at the program.

191
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:26,000
We were not standing next to her.

192
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:28,000
Did you have a sense that she had trouble before that?

193
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:31,000
You know, you were there, did she miss her?

194
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:33,000
No, she didn't.

195
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:34,000
And I had core music.

196
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:39,000
You know, it was guys who would say, look, things like, will we sound a Negro spiritual?

197
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:41,000
I'm going to ride to chair you.

198
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:44,000
You want us to sing like, you know, the end word.

199
00:15:44,000 --> 00:15:48,000
And so, you know, they used that quite frequently at times.

200
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:54,000
Was that unusual for a white core group to be singing in the other spiritual?

201
00:15:54,000 --> 00:15:56,000
I think it was the teacher.

202
00:15:56,000 --> 00:15:59,000
She was a lot, she missed Kelly, was real good.

203
00:15:59,000 --> 00:16:02,000
So she, she, she in core, the reader too.

204
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:06,000
I don't know, but I'm going to ride to chair you in the morning Lord.

205
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:10,000
And then, then, bones, then, bones, then, dry bones.

206
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:13,000
Which, disconnect those bones, then, dry bones.

207
00:16:13,000 --> 00:16:20,000
So, I had others, aren't usual, but did, she did.

208
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:22,000
Well, that's interesting.

209
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:27,000
So, I guess, the disheart, those that are parents with, she just,

210
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:28,000
Right, right.

211
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:31,000
She was a night grader, so she knew her parents was coming.

212
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:36,000
And I don't know what type of repercussion she was going to suffer as a result.

213
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:39,000
But, I guess she knew her parents better than I would.

214
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:43,000
But then, once, I guess, and Kelly always selected the third period.

215
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:45,000
I had a friend in the fourth period.

216
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:46,000
I know the African American.

217
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:51,000
We were only two eight graders, but schedules were identical to classes.

218
00:16:51,000 --> 00:16:54,000
But, they put her in class by herself.

219
00:16:54,000 --> 00:16:57,000
If I went to core music, third period, she went fourth period.

220
00:16:57,000 --> 00:16:59,000
If I went home, I went to home economics.

221
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:01,000
Fifth period, she went sixth period.

222
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:05,000
But, they did put us in the same home room.

223
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:07,000
Twenty minutes a day.

224
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:12,000
So, that's the only time I got a chance to other than core music to kind of exercise my jaws.

225
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:15,000
We got together for that twenty minutes.

